","Abt 950":"omkring 0950","1068":"1068","about 1008":"omkring 1008","1045":"1045","0915":"0915","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrig","Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrig","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrig","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrig","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Basse-Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"950–1008":"0950–1008","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0966–1045":"0966–1045","0984–Female":"0984–Overleden","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0915–1008":"0915–1008","0915–Female":"0915–Overleden","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","950":"0950","Abt 950":"circa 0950","1068":"1068","about 1008":"circa 1008","1045":"1045","0915":"0915","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"950–1008":"0950–1008","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0966–1045":"0966–1045","0984–Female":"0984–Deceased","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0915–1008":"0915–1008","0915–Female":"0915–Deceased","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","950":"0950","Abt 950":"about 0950","1068":"1068","about 1008":"about 1008","1045":"1045","0915":"0915","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh II de Beauchamp was born in 0950, in Normandy, France, his father, Hugh I de Beauchamp, was 35 and his mother, de Beauchamp, was 36. He married Matilda Haie in Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1008, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"950–1008":"0950–1008","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0966–1045":"0966–1045","0984–Female":"0984–Surnud","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0915–1008":"0915–1008","0915–Female":"0915–Surnud","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","950":"0950","Abt 950":"umbes 0950","1068":"1068","about 1008":"umbes 1008","1045":"1045","0915":"0915","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"950–1008":"0950–1008","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0966–1045":"0966–1045","0984–Female":"0984–Kuollut","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0915–1008":"0915–1008","0915–Female":"0915–Kuollut","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","950":"0950","Abt 950":"noin 0950","1068":"1068","about 1008":"noin 1008","1045":"1045","0915":"0915","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vieilles Landes, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Vielles, N